                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Riemann sums give us a way to estimate the net signed area between a curve and the input
                            axis. We can combine this with calculus tools to compute area exactly.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>Definition: Definite Integral</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            The <term>definite integral</term> of a continuous function <m>f(x)</m> on an interval 
                            <m>[a,b]</m> is the number 
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int_a^b f(x) \quad dx = \lim_{n \to \infty} R_n</m>.
                        </p>
                        
                    </solution>
                </exercise>

            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                               <m>\displaystyle \int_0^1 3x \quad dx</m> 
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                We recognize this as the area of a triangle with base <m>1</m> and height <m>3</m>, so
                                <m>\displaystyle \int_0^1 3x \quad dx = 3/2</m> .
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                               <m>\displaystyle \int_{-1}^4 2-2x \quad dx</m> 
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                         <solution>
                            <p>
                                We recognize this as the area of a triangle with base <m>2</m> and height <m>4</m> minus 
                                the area of a triangle with base <m>3</m> and height <m>6</m>, so
                                <m>\displaystyle  \int_{-1}^4 2-2x = 4 - 9 = -5</m> .
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                               <m>\displaystyle \int_{-1}^1 \sqrt{1-x^2} \quad dx</m> 
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                         <solution>
                            <p>
                                We recognize this as the area of a semi-circle with radius <m>1</m>, so
                                <m>\displaystyle  \int_{-1}^1 \sqrt{1-x^2}  \quad dx = \pi/2</m> .
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Properties of Definite Integrals</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\displaystyle \int_a^a f(x) \quad dx = 0</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\displaystyle \int_a^c f(x) \quad dx = \int_a^b f(x) \quad dx + \int_b^c f(x) \quad dx</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\displaystyle \int_a^b f(x) \quad dx = - \int_b^a f(x) \quad dx  </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\displaystyle \int_a^b kf(x) \quad dx = k \int_a^b f(x) \quad dx  </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\displaystyle \int_a^b f(x) + g(x) \quad dx = \int_a^b f(x) \quad dx + \int_a^b g(x) \quad dx</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Practice: Properties of Definite Integrals</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Compute <m>\displaystyle \int_{-3}^4 g(x) \quad dx</m>.
                            <image source="piece-g.jpeg" width="50%">
                                <shortdescription>Graph of a piecwise function g.</shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int_{-3}^4 g(x) \quad dx = 1/2 + \pi/4 - 1/2 - 1 - 1/2 +\pi/2 = 3\pi/4 - 3/2</m>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

